Democracy without People's Connection
Something has happened to democracy in the sense that the government is elected by the people, but it has happened everywhere in the world.
Somehow, people have lost faith in elections.
The turnout at elections has been declining in many countries; in the case of European Parliament elections, the turnout was so laughably low that the legitimacy of the election result is questionable.
Aside from the turnout at elections, we have grown accustomed to considering parties or candidates who received 25% of the votes cast as "winners".
From Holland to Finland and from Argentina to Japan, majorities are being formed based on minorities.
Even the apparent exceptions do not prove the opposite.
Only a few American presidents have been elected by more than 10% of eligible voters. In fact, half of the eligible voters in the US do not even register to vote; of those who register, half do not vote; and of those who do vote, less than half vote for the winner.
Even Tony Blair's "breakthrough" majority in the British House of Commons is on shaky ground: The Labour Party received just over 40% of the votes in the last election in 2002 and that at a turnout of 60%.
Accordingly, only 24% of the total electorate supported Blair's party.
In most countries, things look very different at elections than they did twenty or fifty years ago.
What has happened?
One possible answer is that voters no longer trust the political parties.
Elections in most countries function thanks to intermediaries, organizations that put forward candidates who stand for certain packages of political possibilities, for a "manifesto" or "election programme".
For a variety of reasons, this tried and tested practice no longer works.
Ideological party programmes have lost their power; voters no longer accept the packages tied up by the parties, they want to take something out for themselves and select it.
Furthermore, political parties have become machines that consist of strictly organised teams of insiders.
The paradox here is that the parties have become even more clique-like with the loss of their specific ideological orientation.
It is more important to belong to them than to share their specific convictions.
Such developments have alienated the parties from the voter.
Since most people do not want to belong to a particular party, only a minority is now playing the party game.
This is also increasing the public's suspicion towards political parties - among other things, because it is expensive to play along, similar to professional sports.
If the costs are borne by the taxpayer, it is felt as negative.
However, without the financial support from the state, the parties would have to obtain money through channels that are often rather dubious, if not even illegal.
Many of the major political scandals of the last few decades began with the financing of parties and their candidates.
Other indicators such as the clear decline in memberships confirm that parties have become unpopular.
Yet, parties are indispensable for a representative democracy.
The result is an obvious separation between the visible political actors and the electorate.
Since parties are active in the parliaments, the effects of this separation concern one of the most important institutions of democracy.
People no longer believe that the parliaments represent them and thus equip them with the necessary legitimacy to make decisions on their behalf.
At this point, a second, fairly independent development comes into play.
The people are today more impatient than ever before.
As consumers, they are accustomed to immediate satisfaction.
However, as voters, they have to wait before they feel the results of the election, which they have decided on at the ballot box.
They sometimes do not see the desired results.
The democracy needs time not only for the elections, but also for discussions and wise deliberation.
The consumer as voter will not accept this, however, and therefore turns away.
There are alternatives. But each has its own problems as a democratic solution.
The "direct action" through demonstrations has become a regular and often effective event.
For less mobile people, it could be replaced by the possibility of expressing an opinion electronically; this ranges from Internet chat pages to electronic messages to political leaders.
Then there are the non-governmental organizations. They often have undemocratic structures, but they still seem to be closer to the citizens.
Naturally, there is also the possibility of completely switching off and leaving politics to the experts, in order to concentrate on other focuses of life.
This likely harbors the greatest risks, because it promotes creeping authoritarianism, which is a sign of our time.
But also the other signs of the separation between politics and citizens create a rather insecure state, because no one can say anymore how representative the prevailing opinions are.
Some want to break the knot through more direct democracy.
However, a lasting connection between leaders and the led cannot be established by reducing public discussion to simple voting options.
There are even more reasons to hold on to the classical institutions of parliamentary democracy and try to link them again to the citizenry.
After all, unpopular parties and declining voter turnout could prove to be a temporary phenomenon.
New parties could emerge and bring more life to elections and representative governments.
However, this is likely not enough to restore the overall legitimacy that elected governments have lost.
Therefore, the first concern of all those who place freedom in the Constitution at heart must be to rethink democracy and its institutions.
